<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,151,463]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,295,320]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Stauffer, Bowers, Kellogg &amp; McKaye, 1997" authorityName="Stauffer, Bowers, Kellogg &amp; McKaye" authorityYear="1997" box="[359,594,296,320]" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Metriaclima" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sciasma">
<emphasis box="[359,594,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Metriaclima sciasma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has an extensive distribution north of the Ruhuhu River in the northeastern part of Lake 
<collectingCountry box="[304,389,332,357]" name="Malawi" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Malaŵi</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[408,476,332,356]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1266,1289]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,196,1245]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,193,1245]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Map of Lake MalaŴi showing the locations of species discussed throughout the text." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/204915/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Fig. 
<number box="[463,476,332,356]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). The river and the sandy shores south of Mbamba Bay form a geographic barrier between 
<taxonomicName authority="Stauffer, Bowers, Kellogg &amp; McKaye, 1997" authorityName="Stauffer, Bowers, Kellogg &amp; McKaye" authorityYear="1997" box="[251,378,369,392]" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Metriaclima" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sciasma">
<emphasis box="[251,378,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">M. sciasma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the other members of the 
<taxonomicName authority="Stauffer, Bowers, Kellogg &amp; McKaye, 1997" authorityName="Stauffer, Bowers, Kellogg &amp; McKaye" authorityYear="1997" box="[720,799,368,392]" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Metriaclima" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="23" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aurora">Aurora</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,151,463]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,404,428]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet, 
<taxonomicName authority="Stauffer, Bowers, Kellogg &amp; McKaye, 1997" authorityName="Stauffer, Bowers, Kellogg &amp; McKaye" authorityYear="1997" box="[573,663,405,428]" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Metriaclima" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sciasma">
<emphasis box="[573,663,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">sciasma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is Greek for shadow, in reference to the black pelvic fins of males. It is treated as a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
